We may find a lrey to this in the brief record of the submission of the Chauci² (possibly coupled with that of the western part of the Angrivarii ⁸), and may suppose that to secure the whole lower country to the Weser by the enrolment of this widespread people⁴ in the Roman ranlrs' was a worthy object for this circuit. Thence the whole united army is flung upon the Bructeri, another eagle recovered, and this powerful tribe lopped off from the resources of Arminius ⁵. Passing over the burial of the remains of the army of Varus* as a mere episode suggested by nearness to the spot, and unduly amplified by reason of its capabilities for pictoresque description, we can see that the remaining object of the campaign would be to bring the main body of the enemy to battle, and inflict such a defeat as should crush all remaining resistance to the Weser. Somewhere between the Ems and that river a battle is delivered, but its result is unsatisfactory, and it is therefore brielly described ⁷, and followed by an immediate retreat, turned into a ‘clades ⁸⁹ by the straits and narrow escape of the army of Caecina, and the almost total loss of the baggage and supplies both of this force⁹ and of the two legions nearly drowned through their inexperience of equinoctial tides ¹⁰.
